  "plot_summary": "[HANG0] * This month's <i>Marvel Bullpen Bulletins</i> was sufficiently large to force the <i>Mighty Marvel Checklist</i> onto another page entirely, sharing space with another half-page ad about the <i>MarvelMania International</i> club.\n\n[HANG0] * As for the <i>MBB</i>, the opening item plugs the return of John Romita back in the role of regular penciler, starting this month in [LINK:1969:ASM_82|ASM #82], with more of an emphasis on the life of Peter Parker <i>\"as so many of you have requested</i>.\"\n\n[HANG0] * It is also announced that former Marvel staffer, Jerry Siegel (co-creator of DC's Superman - his Marvel career being very brief) had moved to the West Coast and that their daughter had won a scholarship to UCLA.&nbsp; (This would be just about right, as he had a daughter named Laura, who was born in 1951.)\n\n[HANG0] * <i>Heh</i>, my favorite announcement was where Marvel announces:&nbsp; <i>Starting sooner or later, in some ish or other, we're gonna try using <b>PERIODS</b> instead of those furshlugginer <b>EXCLAMATION POINTS</b> with which we've been ending every sentence since comics began!</i>\n[BR]\n[BR]But they warn that it might be months before readers see the change due to printing delays, and they wonder:&nbsp; <i>Will anyone give a hoot</i>?\n[BR]\n[BR](For the record, I was halfway into my [LINK:1969:ASM_82|ASM #82] plot summary when I suddenly noticed the panels were full of with <i>periods</i> rather than exclamation marks - or is that: <i>exclamation marks!!!!!!!</i>  I was actually <i>surprised</i> I even noticed...)\n\n[HANG0] * Apparently <i>Rawhide Kid</i>, drawn by the notoriously slow Larry Lieber is going to have to speed things up, because the reliable mag is transitioning to <i>monthly</i>!\n\n[HANG0] * <i>Stan's Soapbox</i> discusses the means by which comics are created, including the fact that writers and artists essentially come together to hammer out a basic plot, after which the artist goes off and draws whatever he or she likes (<i>because, unlike other comic-mag publishers, Marvel believes the artist contributes as much to the story as the writer does</i>), after which time, the writer slaps on the text, a letterer steps in to print all the copy in the right places, followed by inking (\"<i>embellisher</i>\"), copying, and finally coloring of one of the copies as a guide to the printers.&nbsp; Finally, the printed copies are distributed nationwide to <i>your friendly neighborhood magazine dealer whose tender loving heart goes pitty-pat every time you buy one</i>!\n\n[HANG0] * While this wasn't an announcement, per se, the inner flap of the covers to this month's magazines features the first appearance (at least that I remember) of Mr. Universe winner Arnold Schwarzenegger, in all his muscled (and pre-<i>Terminator</i>) glory.&nbsp; The ad was for the Joe Weider muscle-building course, but for me, the stunning visage of a very young Schwarzenegger was kind of funny.\n\n[HANG0] * Also, later in the magazine, there's a full-page ad commemorating the 50<sup>th</sup> anniversary of the NFL that offered four miniature plastic replicas of helmets, all for $1 (plus 25 cents shipping).\n[BR]\n[BR]What's more remarkable to a modern reader is the fact that when it says \"NFL,\" they really <i>meant</i> it, and none of the four offered sets featured any of the AFL teams of the day, 1969 being the last season prior to the merger of the two professional football leagues (even down to the fact that, at the time, all three of the teams that later moved to the AFC <i>were</i> listed, those being the Cleveland Browns, Baltimore Colts and Pittsburgh Steelers, which was necessary since there were only 10 AFL teams at the time, as opposed to 16 in the NFL, and the transfer of these three balanced what would eventually become the AFC and NFC conferences).\n[BR]\n[BR] [SPAN: severity=info; fonttype=bold; text=<i>Hey</i>, you never know what you're going to learn on this website!]",
